<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40093a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40093a">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40093a"> 93(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ shagpiled rugs / his sitting was upon / green scarlet</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Hereupon the Sage adopted his nephew Nadan &hellip;; so he entrusted him to eight wet-nurses and dry-nurses for feeding and rearing, and they brought him up on diet the choicest with delicatest nurture and clothed him with sendal and escalate and dresses dyed with Alkermes, and his sitting was shag-piled rugs of silk. <small> Richard F. Burton, trans. <a name="RFBS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RFBS"><cite title="source">Supplemental Nights to the Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night with Notes Anthropological and Explanatory</cite></a> (n.d.) xvi.2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Burton observes: (2.n2) [Escarlate] <i>i.e.</i> a woollen cloth dyed red. Hence Pyrand(i. 244) has &ldquo;red scarlet,&rdquo; &hellip; Froissart (xvth centry.) has &ldquo;white scarlet,&rdquo; and Marot (xvith) has &ldquo;green scarlet,&rdquo;; and, (3.n1) <i>i.e.</i> &ldquo;Al-kirm,&rdquo; Arab. and Persian. = a worm, as in Kirm&aacute;n (see Supplemen. vol. i.40); the <i>coccus ilicis</i>, vulg. called cochineal. </mm> </dd></dl>
